bug.short_desc: OutOfMemoryErrors not handled gracefully

long_desc.thetext:
Our product (RAD) which builds on top of Eclipse, sometimes has many Eclipse jobs running. If the JVM throws an OutOfMemoryError, a dialog appears that offers to close Eclipse, but (it looks like) all of the other jobs continue to try to run.
Clicking on the dialog to close Eclipse, usually doesn't work. The main window goes away but the process continues to run (forever?). You end up having to kill it from something like the task manager.
If the user asks for Eclipse to shutdown, it should really shutdown.

When it is running forever after the main window goes away, do you see a progress dialog, or nothing at all? If you are seeing a progress dialog, it should have a "details" area where the user can cancel any job that is conflicting with the shutdown. We don't cancel those jobs gratuitously, because it might be something that the user really doesn't want to cancel... so, we leave it up to the user to decide.
If you are not seeing a progress dialog, it means the workspace save has completed, and the OSGi shutdown process has run. If the process stays alive, it means those background jobs were asked to cancel, but they never exited. The Java VM does not exit until all non-daemon threads exit. I suggest getting a stack dump in this situation to see what the mis-behaving jobs are.
Related: bug 33972

bug.short_desc: reduce pointcut to staticly-determinable form, find shadow?

long_desc.thetext:
Consider static(pc()) and/or shadow(pc()) defined as the staticly-determinable form of a pointcut and the shadows picked out by the pointcut.
Why:
declare error/warning support only staticly-determinable pointcuts. It's sort of a pain to manually reduce them for the purposes of debugging pointcuts, especially where the pointcut is named and composed. It would be nice to have the function static(pc()) which, given a pointcut, returns the staticly-determinable portion of it. This is essential when one is debugging pointcuts for which one has no source.
For this use-case, it would be used only in declare error or warning.
The second use-case for static(pc()) is when a pointcut is defined to bind variables, but someone wants to use the same pointcut without doing any runtime checking. (It's already possible to supply the types to check but not bind.) This would make it possible to find join points that would be matched but for the variable binding. Again, this might be helpful to reuse binary pointcuts.
The difference between static(pc()) and shadow(pc()) is determined by implementation-specific optimizations. For DEOW we've defined this(SpecificType) to not be staticly-determinable because we like the bright-line rule based on primitive pointcut designators. The simplest implementation would follow this rule, and it would be cleanest for DEOW use.
However, it might be helpful to surface implementation-specific optimizations, i.e., the actual join point shadow. Assuming an implementation does determine staticly that this(SpecificType) can be rewritten as
within(SpecificType) && !within(SpecificType..*)
then shadow(pc()) would produce the same optimizations rather than pruning out this(SpecificType) entirely. It would be permitted for an implementation to return the infinite pointcut (this(Foo) || !this(Foo)), but not to return a pointcut that picks out any join point that would never be picked out at runtime.
I think it would be quite helpful for comparing implementations to have a way to test their differences on this point; that includes comparing old and new versions of AspectJ.
Naming: my initial thoughts were "static(pc)" and "shadow(pc())". "static" is bad because it's already used in too many ways. "staticlyDeterminable(pc())" is just bad, and "determinable "shadow" and "woven" is bad because we don't want people thinking in terms of shadows (except perhaps when we do). "structure(pc())" is not bad for shadows, and perhaps "implementation(pc())" or "implemented(pc())" is even more obvious.
(Of course, these are just some of the pointcut-rewriting functions that could be useful. E.g., at the user level, I can imagine abstract aspects being extended by aspects rewriting their pointcuts rather than redefining them. For that we'd end up defining a canonical representation and API's for traversal and modification.)

bug.short_desc: [hotbug] [validation] Validation builder launches a job that causes build to cancel

long_desc.thetext:
Build: Eclipse 3.2.1, WTP 1.5.1.
Background: Auto-build is a "polite" job. If it sees that another job with a resource scheduling rule is waiting to run, it aborts the build process to allow that job to run. The reasoning is that there is no point building if there is a job waiting to modify the workspace, which may cause the build effort to be wasted.
In WTP 1.5, the WST validation builder was changed to fork background jobs for certain types of validators (bug 91563). Now the fun begins. Here is the process flow I have been observing while debugging an unrelated problem:
1) A file in the workspace is modified by the user 2) Autobuild starts running 3) The validation builder forks a background job 4) Autobuild notices that a job is waiting, and aborts the autobuild 5) The validation job runs 6) Autobuild starts again
Thus the validation job and the autobuild job are thrashing against each other. Even worse, if any thread modifies the workspace between 4) and 6), then the validation builder will run again. In theory at least, this could cause indefinite churn as the auto-build and background validation kick each other into action. The autobuild behaviour is designed under the assumption that jobs with resource scheduling rules are likely to modify the workspace. I instrumented the SSE ModelManagerImpl and its cache is basically rendered useless on larger workspaces. What we do is let each validator validate a long list of files. We have a race going on. It may be overkill for some validators to lock the entire workspace, but that likely depends on the validator. Some validators could be checking for referential integrity across multiple files in multiple projects (think of a link checker for HTML), that would have difficulty handling concurrent changes. Other validators that act only on single files in isolation may not require any locking at all (workspace reads require no locks). The issue here is that when Autobuild starts, it triggers the EJB Validation. Since EJB Validation is a non-system job, autobuild then politely backs off, and lets EJB validation run. Once the ejb validation runs, it again kicks autobuild off, which triggers EJB validation and the cycle continues for an indefinite period of time.
This issue becomes highly repeatable and affects performance in large complex workspaces that have cyclical dependencies.
In order to fix this, the patch attached above creates a 'ValidatorLauncherJob' which is a system job. The only thing this job does is launch the actual validation job, and we now schedule the validatorlauncherjob instead of directly scheduling the validationjob. Since autobuild does not stop when a system job is waiting, it now runs to completion without interruption by ejb validation, which is followed by the scheduling and execution of the ejb validation jobs.

bug.short_desc: [content type] IContentType.isKindOf returns false even though argument is target's base type

long_desc.thetext:
This might not be a bug, maybe just incorrect usage on my part.
I try to obtain a matcher using a custom selection policy:
IContentTypeMatcher matcher = contentTypeManager.getMatcher(new MySelectionPolicy(), null);
This selection policy only allows content types that inherit from a certain fixed base type. So I obtain the base type:
IContentType baseType = contentTypeManager.getContentType("my.content.type");
In the seletion policy, I try to determine if the candidate "isKindOf" the base type:
public IContentType[] select(IContentType[] candidates, boolean fileName, boolean content) { ... if (candidates[i].isKindOf(baseType)) ...
The problem is, I always get "false", even for types that clearly inherit from the base type (even the base type itself).
The problem seems to be in ContentType.isKindOf method: the candidate's dynamic type is "ContentType", but baseType is "ContentTypeHandler". ContentType.isKindOf uses reference equality for comparison (rather than comparing the ids, for example).
ContentTypeHandler.isKindOf first unwraps the target (ContentType), so that should work.
My question is, should they be symmetrical, or am I using it wrong?

It is a bug indeed. The idea was that client code would never be given instances of ContentType, only ContentTypeHandlers (to avoid leaks in the case a new content type catalog is built). ISelectionPolicy is clearly a case where this rule was broken. It was never noticed before because the only implementation we had in the platform (in the resources plug-in) didn't call isKindOf.
I would say it would be ok if the content type manager kept passing in instances of ContentType because selection policies are unlikely to hold them (ISelectionPolicy is more of a SPI than a regular API). Then, changing ContentType.isKindOf to only check the id should be enough to fix this problem.

bug.short_desc: Asynchronous viewer should allow model to set selection after selected object is removed.

long_desc.thetext:
To elaborate: When the selected object is removed in Debug view, the selection is lost and no other item is selected unless a model event causes a new selection. For example, if a JDT stack frame is selected, and then the resume action is invoked, the selection in debug view is lost, which in turn causes the run control actions to be disabled.
I don't know the internals of JDT, but in our product, we have a similar problem where the resume event is issued on the debug target, even if the resume request was submitted to a thread. This is annoying for some users who have to re-select the thread in order to suspend it again.
I'm submitting a patch which adds a new IModelSelectionPolicy.retrieveInvalidSelectionReplacemement() method, which allows the model to set a new selection to replace the old selection which was invalid. I'm not sure if adding this method (and yet another async request monitor) is an overkill, but it seems to work OK. An acceptable alternative may be to just select the parent node of the invalid selection just within the AsynchronousTreeViewer.handleInvalidSelection()
Created an attachment (id=51510) Patch adding the new IModelSelectionPolicy.retrieveInvalidSelectionReplacemement() method.

I would prefer that the model proxy direct the selection in this case. In the case of the default model, when a thread is resumed, that thread is selected via a model delta (so the selection goes from the frame to the thread).

To explain the use case a little further:
We have a debugger which controls the processor directly through a JTAG connection, and it can only suspend or resume the entire processor. But we also have logic which tracks the kernel tasks and processes which are running on this processor, and we represent these in the Debug view. So the processor is the "Debug target" node, and the kernel tasks are the "Thread" nodes. When the user goes to resume a task, the debug engine only tells us that the whole processor is resumed. And from this event we cannot tell the Debug view which thread to select.
So when I first started on this problem, I also assumed that the model proxy would be the place to fix this, but I quickly realized that the proxy doesn't have enough information. Because, the logical thing to do from the user's point of view, is to re-select the thread which owned the stack frame that was selected when the processor was resumed. Unfortunately, the model proxy doesn't have ready access to the current selection in the viewer and that's where I got stuck. I suppose that the model proxy could extract the viewer and the selection using the IPresentationContext, but I thought that a much cleaner solution would be to let IModelSelectionPolicy handle the loss of selection, since it already is the go-to adapter for selection issues.
Incidentally, prior to flexible hierarchy, Debug view did seem to implement some logic to handle this case, because it hasn't been an issue before.
Thanks -Pawel
I plan to update the patch for the new viewer APIs within next couple of weeks.

Created an attachment (id=57139) Patch for M5
I updated the patch targeted for M5.
I also changed the approach slightly. Instead of adding an aynchronous method to IModelSelectionPolicy, which required the selection policy to update the viewer after the selection is lost, I made the replace method to be synchronous. This greatly simplifies the implementation and reduces flicker in the view. If the model requires the new selection to be calculated asynchronously, it can still do so, and then generate an update using the IModelProxy.
As it is, I hope that the change in this patch is a simple and logical extension of functionality of IModelSelectionPolicy interface :-)

Before implementing this service, a decision needs to be made which approach to take.

bug.short_desc: 3.2 displays read only ".class" views of source code in projects

long_desc.thetext:
when jumping to source code from the stack trace in the console, eclipse 3.2 behaves differently than eclipse 3.1.
in 3.1, the link always jumped to the ".java" file, and the file could be editted. in 3.2 the link always seems to jump to a read only ".class" view of the source code. this may be because the class is also contained in a jar file which is built by eclipse and used by some projects instead of a direct project reference.
however, with the same scenario in 3.1, the stack trace links to the ".java" file and not a read only ".class" view of the file.
when maintaining code, stack traces are a central element for fixing and repairing software.
when you jump to a read only view of source code, this is very frustrating. the purpose of a development environment is to edit code, and not view read only representations of source code.
when using 3.2, you constantly need to use ctrl-shift-t and ctrl-l to find the location of stack trace entries in the .java files, because the read only ".class" views are totally useless.

The stack trace console searches the entire workspace for source in a non-deterministic order. The console output from a program searches the source path of the associated program (i.e. corresponding to the program's classpath). Thus, the stack trace console may locate incorrect source if there are duplicates in the workspace (due to the search order). The stack trace console does not have a context in which to lookup source, other than the entire workspace.
I don't think there's anything we can do about this, unless we add features to the stack trace console to provide it a context or working set filter.

the search in the classpath does not seem to work properly. for example, if the project is before the jar file in the project class path, then the java file is shown. however, if you only put the project first in the launcher class path, then the .class file is shown.
There is a fix in 3.2.2 that might fix your problem. See bug 166113. Please let us know if this fixes the problem, so we can mark this as a dup.

bug.short_desc: Add "COLLAPSE" flag to IModelDelta

long_desc.thetext: For some debugger backends all threads are resumed/suspended when the step command is issued. Expanding all of them is very costly, only the so-called current thread needs to be expanded. If the current thread changes during the stepping, the old expanded thread needs to be collapsed.

The model proxy for the debugger should be able to control this. The default model proxy assumes a single thread is suspended/resumed when stepping. However, a custom model proxy could account for all threads suspending/resuming and only expand/collapse the important thread. We could add a COLLAPSE flag, but I'm not sure that we need one, since when the thread is resumed, it can also be "CONTENT" change which will effectively collapse it (get rid of its children/frames).

(In reply to comment #1) > I'm not sure that we need one, since when the thread is resumed, it can > also be "CONTENT" change which will effectively collapse it (get rid of its > children/frames).
That's what we do on "resume". At this point only the "stepping" thread keeps his children. In the current implementation when the step is done we fire only one suspend event from the current thread. When I try to fire suspend events from all thread the previously expanded thread expands as well. My guess is the view saves the previous state and restores it when the step is complete. Firing "COLLAPSE" could be a solution if my assumption is correct. Unfortunately, at the moment I don't have access to the environment to reproduce the problem and it may be to late when I get it.
Added COLLAPSE flag to IModelDelta, and handling in ModelContentProvdier/TreeModelContentProvider.
Please verify, Curtis.
Verified

When searching for a type, we try all sorts of whacky combinations in an attempt to locate it (if it isn't fully qualified we have to search, using imports, etc).
Now we support the flag 'allowMissing' when looking for a type, this is true if you are asking the world for a type and your not sure whether it is there or not, and you can continue processing if its not there. OK, figured it out. Two projects has the same bundle symbolic name. Each workspace model should have a IModelEntry (this keeps track of the workspace model, external model, and the PDE classpath container). We find all the plug-in projects then create ModelEntries for each. The ModelEntries are then stored by bundle-symbolic name.
A ModelEntry can have only one workspace model, since PDE does not support multiple plug-ins with same bundle-symbolic name. So when we initialize a project's classpath container, we find its bundle-symbolic name. We then find the corresponding ModelEntry. We then update the classpath container in the ModelEntry object. But in this case, since two projects had the same bundle-symbolic name, they both resolved to the same ModelEntry.
For instance, say P1 and P2 both have the bundle-symbolicName P1. We created a ModelEntry with the bundle-SymbolicName P1 and set the workspace project to P1. But since P2 has the same bundle-SymbolicName, we then set the ModelEntry for the id P1, to the P2 workspace project. When we initialized project P1, we found the bundle-symbolicName and found the corresponding ModelEntry (which contained a reference to P2). We then updated the classpath container for the workspace project specified in the ModelEntry (P2). Therefore, every time we tried to initialize P1, we kept initializing P2 instead.
The fix is simple. When initializing the classpath container, we have an IProject which represents the project getting initialized. Once we get the ModelEntry back, we check to make sure the workspace project it references is the same as the project we are trying to initialize. If they don't match, we don't do anything which will leave the container uninitialized (but will stop infinite loops). Note, this will leave the container "unbounded". I am not sure if this is the exact behavior we want, but it will tell the user they have a Plug-in Dependency classpath container issue.

For each thread end event there must be preceding thread start event. But it was reproduced that in multithreading scenarios some thread start events were missing.
Reproduced on different configurations:
EM64T Configuration: Build: javaprofiler.all_platforms-TPTP-4.3.0-200610010100 - linux_em64t JRE: jrockit-jdk1.5.0-linux-em64t OS: SUSE 9 64-bit PATCHLEVEL = 3 on 4xXeon x64 (Tulsa, 2cores, 16Mb L3)
IA32 Configuration: Build: javaprofiler.all_platforms-TPTP-4.3.0-200610010100 - linux_ia32 JRE: jrockit-jdk1.5.0-linux-ia32 JRE: sun-jdk1.5.0_06-linux-ia32 OS: SUSE 9 32-bit PATCHLEVEL = 2 on 2xXeon x64 / IBM xSeries 336 OS: SUSE 9 32-bit PATCHLEVEL = 2 on 2xXeon ia32 / HP Proliant DL360 G3
Created an attachment (id=51528) Trace example with missing thread start events (mtPlainWorkload100F)
Working on it
I have verified that Martini generates Thread Start events for all threads referenced in Method Enter, Method Leave and Thread End events. This is a CGProf bug. Reassigning to Slava.

This bug caused by unsynchronized Linux C function write(), which is used for writing output data into file. This bug is reproduced only on multi-core platforms. Due to this bug some output events are lost in output file. To fix the bug the function write() should be included in critical section.
bug fixed

bug.short_desc: VM crash when hitting tab button in a textfield

long_desc.thetext:
Szenario: We have a MultiPageEditorTab with textField, combos and tables in it.
Description: 1.) Set the focus to the first textField in this MultiPageEditorTab. 2.) Push the tab button on the keyboard to jump to the next textfield. 3.) The VM crashes. See the hs_err_pid4364.log.
We noticed: 1.) This problem occurs not on every Computer where we try to reproduce this crash. - is not reproduceable on Fujitsu Siemens Notebooks - it happens sometimes on our Dell Desktop Pc ( see hardware-env in the errorlog )
2.) It is quite a complex MultiPageEditor where we have several nested composites, till finally the widgets ( text, combo, tables ) are added.
3.) We are using formtoolkit
